    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Aug. 8<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1881</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>Pray forgive me for troubling you.— I have forgotten who published the translation of Weismann’s book.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> My copy of the first Part has been mislaid &amp; I cannot find it, high or low, but it cannot be lost. The publisher has never sent me Part II &amp; I want to write to him to ask him to do so. &amp; to enquire whether I paid for Part II, as it is my usual habit to pay for all parts in advance to save loss of time.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
                    <p>I am glad to see how extremely flourishing your Essex Club appears to be<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>My dear Sir | Yours very faithfully | Charles Darwin</p>
<p>Several persons have spoken to me with interest about Weismann’s book—</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">1.1 the translation of 1.2] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n2">1.4 write to] ‘to’ <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
            </div>
            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Meldola had translated <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5050.xml">August Weismann</ref>’s <hi rend="italic">Studien zur Descendenz-Theorie</hi> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_10916.xml">Weismann 1875–6</ref>); the translation was published in three parts by the London firm of Sampson Low, Marston, Searle, &amp; Rivington (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_10712.xml">Weismann 1880–2</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Part 1 of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_10712.xml">Weismann 1880–2</ref> was published in 1880; part 2 was published in 1881. The work was paid for by subscription (see <hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 27, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11861.xml">letter from Raphael Meldola, 6 February 1879</ref>). CD’s Classed account book (Down House MS) records a payment of £1 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. on 7 May 1880 to ‘Sampson Low for Weisman’; no further payments are recorded. CD’s copy of all three parts of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_10712.xml" resp="#automat" cert="low">Weismann 1880–2</ref> are in the Darwin Library–Down.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Meldola was president of the Epping Forest and County of Essex Naturalists’ Field Club, which was founded in 1880; CD was an honorary member (see <hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 28, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-12480.xml">letter from William Cole, 14 February 1880</ref>).</note>
          
        </div>
    
